Project: Medical Appointment Data Analysis¶

Introduction¶

Data Description¶

This is a Data Analysis on a Medical Appointment Dataset.

This dataset collects information from more than 100k medical appointments in Brazil and is focused of wether or not patients show up for their medical appointments. The analysis will be based on analyzing the different reasons that couls have influenced the patients to show up for their appointment or not.

Here, we are trying to find insights and trends that contributed to patients showing up or not showing up for their medical appointments.

Columns Description¶

For each record, there are 14 variable, which are:

  1. PatientId: The ID of each patient.
  1. AppointmentID: The ID of each appointment.
  1. Gender: The gender of each patient.
  1. ScheduledDay: The day at which the patient set up his appointment.
  1. AppointmentDay: The day at which the patient set up his appointment.
  1. Age: The age of each patient.
  1. Neighbourhood: The place at which the appointment takes place.
  1. Scholarship: It indicates whether the patient is enrolled in Brasilian welfare program or not.
  1. Hipertension: It indicates wether the patient suffers from Hipertension or not.
  1. Diabetes: It indicates wether the patient suffers from Diabetes or not.
  1. Alcoholism: It indicates wether the patient suffers from Alcoholism or not.
  1. Handcap: The number of handicaps that the patient has.
  1. SMS_received: It indicates wether the patient received SMS or not.
  1. No-show: It indicates wether the patient showed up for the appointment or not.

Questions for Analysis¶

  1. Does receiving SMS determine wether the patients show up or not?

    In the no-show appointmenets dataset, some patients recieved sms that were meant to remind them of their appointment dates while some did not. We will find out if this contributed to thier showing up or not.

  1. Does gender determine wether the patients show up or not?

    Some of the patients were males while some were females. We will find out if males were more likely to show up or if the females were more likely to show up for their appointments.

  1. Does closer appointment dates or farther appointment dates contributes to patients showing up or not?

    From the list of given appointment dates, some appointment dates were earlier while some were farther away. We will find out if having a closer appointment dates or having farther appointment dates contributes to patients showing up for their appointments.

  1. Does having appointments during the weekdays or having appointments during the weekend contribute to patients showing up or not?

    We will find out if having appointment dates fixed during the weekdays or during the weekends contributes to the patients showing up for their appointmnets.

  1. Does having a scholarship (a social welfare program by the government of Brazil) contributes to patients showing or not?

    We will find out wether being enrolled in Brasilian welfare in Brazil contributes to patients showing up for thier appointments.

  1. Does a patient suffering from Diabetes contributes to the patient showing up or not?

    This is one of the ailments that some of the patients in the dataset suffered from, and we will find out if suffering from this disease contributes to the patients showng up for their appointments or not.

    """
    This function takes in a numerical variable and returns a boxplot of its distribution
    """
    sns.boxplot(data=df, x=var_name)

Conclusion¶

  • Receiving an sms does not contribute to the willingness to show up for their appointments, as from our analysis, the people that did not receive an sms even showed up more.
  • Being a female or male does not influence their showing up for their appointments as from our analysis, both gender have almost the same percentage of showing up for their appointments.
  • Patients who have a farther appointment dates were more likely to show up than patients with closer appointment dates.
  • Patients whose appointment days fall in during the weekdays were more likely to show up than patients whose appointment days fall in during the weekends.
  • Receiving a scholarship does not have an effect on the patients showing up as those without the scholarship showed up more.
  • Patients who were suffering diabetes were more likely to show up than patients who were not suffering from diabetes.

Limitations¶

  • The conlusions above are based on my understanding of the dataset, so they should be taken as tentative.
  • Even though there are no missing features and duplicate values in our data, statistical tests (t-test, anova) might still be required for final conclusion.
